{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01Fq35xm87ci3pcUrk5N2jWV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this problem: evaluate $I = \\int_0^\\infty t^{-1/2} e^{-1985(t + 1/t)}\\,dt$.\n\n**Substitution $t = u^2$:** Then $dt = 2u\\,du$, $t^{-1/2} = 1/u$, giving\n$$I = 2\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du, \\qquad a = 1985.$$\n\n**Complete the square:** $u^2 + 1/u^2 = (u - 1/u)^2 + 2$, so\n$$I = 2e^{-2a}\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}\\,du.$$\n\n**Glasser-style trick:** Substituting $w = 1/u$ in $\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}\\,du$ gives the same integral but weighted by $1/u^2$. Hence\n$$2\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}\\,du = \\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}(1 + 1/u^2)\\,du.$$\n\n**Final substitution $v = u - 1/u$:** Then $dv = (1 + 1/u^2)\\,du$, and as $u$ ranges over $(0,\\infty)$, $v$ ranges over $(-\\infty, \\infty)$ monotonically. So\n$$\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}(1+1/u^2)\\,du = \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty e^{-av^2}\\,dv = \\sqrt{\\pi/a}.$$\n\nTherefore $\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u-1/u)^2}\\,du = \\tfrac{1}{2}\\sqrt{\\pi/a}$, and\n$$I = 2e^{-2a} \\cdot \\tfrac{1}{2}\\sqrt{\\pi/a} = e^{-2a}\\sqrt{\\pi/a}.$$\n\nWith $a = 1985$:\n\nANSWER: $\\sqrt{\\pi/1985}\\,e^{-3970}$\nCONFIDENCE: high"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":500,"cache_read_input_tokens":19543,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":500},"output_tokens":108,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72331d52-cf17-4aaa-92e6-5a1720beb010","uuid":"92c86af4-7bea-4b52-a43e-65ec03d05abc","request_id":"req_011CbDQPK9yWfQG6Z5ZDRPtq"}
